Q8: You could have had a much more powerful intro if you had started with the image of the fit old guy and said who wouldn't want to look like this guy when they are 65? All of your objectives were covered in the background info. You should have no more than 1/2 of the objectives based on background info. The point of seminar is to present evidence supporting or refuting an idea. An alternative objective could be something like evaluate the data presented to determine if a cardiovascular risk is present with TRT.
Q10: There is much more data for your first study available in the original article in JAMA than you presented. They also provide the reason that their primary outcomes don't appear to show to the results they state in the conclusions. This information is important to include when assessing the validity of the studies you present. By not doing so, you are cannot determine the external validity (and internal validity) of the results and also cannot assess the strengths and weaknesses of the study. A more thorough assessment of the studies presented should be done in your next seminar.
